The docker file, with the from and run instructions.

A docker file is a plain-text recipe for building an image. It's conventionally named docker file, with no extension, and it lives at your project root. The simplest possible one has two lines: a from instruction that picks a base image, and a command instruction that sets what it prints. You build it with docker build, dash t, a name, and a dot, which reads the docker file in the current directory, runs its instructions in order, and tags the new image.

Here's the key mental model for how a build executes. Each instruction either adds a layer or modifies the config blob. The filesystem-changing instructions, run, copy, and add, execute in a temporary container based on the previous layer, and then commit the result as a new layer. The metadata-only instructions, like the command, entry-point, env, work-dir, user, expose, and label, just change the j-son config, with no new bytes. Knowing which kind each instruction is helps you reason about caching and image size.

Every docker file starts with from, which picks the base everything else layers on top of. A few rules of thumb. Official images, like python or node, are maintained by Docker or the language teams, and they're the default choice. The slim variants drop everything not needed for the runtime, so they're smaller with fewer vulnerabilities. The alpine variants are the smallest, but test them, because they use a different C library. Scratch is the literal empty image, a base for statically-linked Go or Rust binaries. And always pin the tag, or even a digest, for repeatable builds.

The run instruction runs a command inside a temporary container and commits the result as a new layer. That's how you install packages and compile code. There are two forms: shell form, which runs through the shell and gives you and-and, pipes, and variable expansion; and exec form, a j-son array, which runs directly with no shell. And here's why you see and-and everywhere: each run makes a new layer, so you chain related steps into one run. Update the package index, install your packages, and clean up the cache, all in a single instruction. That keeps the layer count down, the index fresh, and the image clean.
